<p><b>What is a slur in jazz?</b> A slur is a symbol in Western musical notation indicating that the notes it embraces are to be played without separation (that is, with legato articulation). A slur is denoted with a curved line generally placed over the notes if the stems point downward, and under them if the stems point upwards.</p>
<p><b>Why do jazz guitarists not bend strings?</b> Many Jazz guitar purists choose to use relatively heavy gauge strings - often flat wound - which make string bending difficult and limited compared with the string choice in genres like Blues and Rock, in which players tend to prefer lighter gauge strings which lend themselves more easily to string…</p>
